{"title_page": "1949 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1949 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1949.png\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1949 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting and finishing in Paris\n| image_alt          =\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 30 June \u2013 24 July\n| stages             = 21\n| distance           = 4808\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 145h 36' 56\"\n| first              = [[Fausto Coppi]]\n| first_nat          = ITA\n| first_color        = yellow\n| first_team         = Italy\n| second             = [[Gino Bartali]]\n| second_nat         = ITA\n| second_team        = Italy\n| third              = [[Jacques Marinelli]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| third_team         = \u00cele-de-France\n| team               = Italy\n| mountains          = [[Fausto Coppi]]\n| mountains_nat      = ITA\n| mountains_team     = Italy\n| previous           = [[1948 Tour de France|1948]]\n| next               = [[1950 Tour de France|1950]]\n}}\nThe '''1949 Tour de France''' was the 36th edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place from 30 June to 24 July. It consisted of 21 stages over {{convert|4808|km|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe Italian team had internal problems, because [[Gino Bartali]] and [[Fausto Coppi]] could both be the team leader. During the selection procedure, Coppi almost refused to start the race, but he was convinced to start. During the race, Coppi almost pulled out, because he felt he did not have full support from the team captain. In the Alps, Coppi recovered. The race was won by Coppi, with second place taken by teammate Bartali, the winner of the previous year. Coppi also won the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]], while his Italian team won the [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]].\n\n==Changes from the previous Tour==\nThe 1949 Tour de France marked the first time that the Tour de France had a stage finish in Spain, when it stopped in [[San Sebasti\u00e1n|San Sebastian]] in the ninth stage.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\nWhile the mountains had been categorised into two categories in 1948, in 1949 the third category was added.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=40}}\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1949 Tour de France}}\n\nAs was the custom since the [[1930 Tour de France]], the 1949 Tour de France was contested by national and regional teams. The three major cycling countries in 1949, Italy, Belgium and France, each sent a team of 12 cyclists. Other countries sent teams of 6 cyclists: Switzerland, Luxembourg, Netherlands and Spain. Italy and Belgium also sent two extra teams of young riders of 6 cyclists each.\nThe French regional cyclists were divided into four teams of 12 cyclists: \u00cele-de-France, West/North, Centre/South-West and South-East. Altogether this made 120 cyclists.<ref name=\"mdc1949\"/>\n\nThere were 57 French cyclists, 22 Italian, 18 Belgian, 6 Dutch, 6 Luxembourg, 6 Spanish, 6 Swiss and 1 Polish cyclist.<ref name=\"tgv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tour-giro-vuelta.net|title=Tour-Giro-Vuelta|work=www.tour-giro-vuelta.net|accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref>\nIn the previous year, Fausto Coppi refused to enter the Tour de France because of personal problems with his teammate Gino Bartali. Bartali had won the previous Tour, and was trying to equal [[Philippe Thys]] by winning the Tour three times.<ref name=\"mdc1949\"/> Coppi had won the [[1949 Giro d'Italia]], and wanted to be the first one to achieve the Tour-Giro double in one year. The Italian team manager [[Alfredo Binda]] convinced them two weeks before the start of the race to join forces, so both Italians were in the race.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=40}}\n\nThe teams entering the race were:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Italy\n* Belgium\n* France\n* Switzerland\n* Luxembourg\n* Netherlands\n* Spain\n* Italy Cadets\n* Belgium Aiglons\n* \u00cele-de-France\n* West/North\n* Centre/South-West\n* South-East\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Route and stages==\n\nThe 1949 Tour de France started on 30 June, and had four rest days, in Les Sables-d'Olonne, Pau, Cannes and Aosta.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=40}} The [[List of highest points reached in the Tour de France|highest point of elevation in the race]] was {{convert|2770|m|ft|abbr=on}} at the summit of the [[Col de l'Iseran]] mountain pass on stage 17.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=178}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Bartali-Coppi onweerwolk boven Tour de France|trans-title=Bartali-Coppi storm cloud above Tour de France|url=https://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ABCDDD:010877679:mpeg21:p003|work=[[de Volkskrant]]|date=30 June 1949|page=3|language=Dutch|via=[[Delpher]]}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1949\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1949.php|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=36\u00e8me Tour de France 1949|language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301035656/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1949.php|archive-date=1 March 2012|access-date=26 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=40}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1949 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |first=Arian |last=Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |accessdate=2 December 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516071832/http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archivedate=16 May 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 30 June\n| [[Paris]] to [[Reims]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|182|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Marcel Dussault]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1 July\n| [[Reims]] to [[Brussels]] (Belgium)|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|273|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Roger Lambrecht]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2 July\n| [[Brussels]] (Belgium) to [[Boulogne-sur-Mer]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|211|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Norbert Callens]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3 July\n| [[Boulogne-sur-Mer]] to [[Rouen]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|185|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Lucien Teisseire]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4 July\n| [[Rouen]] to [[Saint-Malo]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|293|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]|SUI}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5 July\n| [[Saint-Malo]] to [[Les Sables-d'Olonne]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|305|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Adolphe Deledda]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Les Sables-d'Olonne]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7 July\n| [[Les Sables-d'Olonne]] to [[La Rochelle]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|92|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] ||{{flagathlete|[[Fausto Coppi]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8 July\n| [[La Rochelle]] to [[Bordeaux]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|262|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Guy Lap\u00e9bie]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9 July\n| [[Bordeaux]] to [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|228|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Louis Caput]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |10\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 10 July\n| [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]] to [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|192|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Fiorenzo Magni]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |11\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12 July\n| [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]] to [[Luchon]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|193|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Jean Robic]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |12\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13 July\n| [[Luchon]] to [[Toulouse]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|134|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Rik Van Steenbergen]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |13\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 14 July\n| [[Toulouse]] to [[N\u00eemes]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|289|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Emile Id\u00e9e]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |14\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 15 July\n| [[N\u00eemes]] to [[Marseille]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|199|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Jean Goldschmidt]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |15\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 July\n| [[Marseille]] to [[Cannes]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|215|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Keteleer]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Cannes]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |16\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 18 July\n| [[Cannes]] to [[Brian\u00e7on]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|275|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |17\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 19 July\n| [[Brian\u00e7on]] to [[Aosta]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|257|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Fausto Coppi]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Aosta]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |18\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 21 July\n| [[Aosta]] to [[Lausanne]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|265|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Vincenzo Rossello]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |19\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 22 July\n| [[Lausanne]] to [[Colmar]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|283|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Rapha\u00ebl G\u00e9miniani]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |20\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 23 July\n| [[Colmar]] to [[Nancy, France|Nancy]]||{{convert|137|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountain Time Trial Stage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial|Mountain time trial]]||{{flagathlete|[[Fausto Coppi]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |21\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 24 July\n| [[Nancy, France|Nancy]] to [[Paris]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|340|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Rik Van Steenbergen]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4808|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=109}}\n|}\n\n==Race overview==\n\n[[File:Tour de France, 2e etappe Reims-Brussel. Finish, Roger Lambrecht en Jacques Marinelli (1949) (cropped).jpg|thumb| [[Roger Lambrecht]] winning the second stage ahead of [[Jacques Marinelli]] at [[King Baudouin Stadium|Heysel Stadium]] in [[Brussels]]]]\nIn the early stages, Bartali and Coppi both lost time. Before the fifth stage, Coppi and Bartali both were not in the top fifteen of the general classification.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=159\u2013165}}\n\nIn that fifth stage, Coppi escaped together with the leader of the general classification, [[Jacques Marinelli]]. When they were leading by 6 minutes, Coppi and Marinelli fell in [[Mouen]].<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> Marinelli was not hurt and could continue, but Coppi's bike was broken. The Italian team car offered him a new one, but Coppi refused because he wanted his personal spare bike, and threatened to quit the race.\n\nWhen Bartali reached Coppi, he saw the problem, and waited. Even later, the Italian team captain Binda arrived with Coppi's spare bike, and Bartali and Coppi started to ride. Coppi started to slow down, complaining he was hungry and exhausted. Bartali decided he could not wait anymore, and rode away from Coppi. Coppi came in 18 minutes late that stage.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=159\u2013165}}\nLater that night, it became clear that Coppi had been angry because the team leader had not been following him, even though he was in the leading group. Coppi did not want to race in a team where Bartali and not he was the leader. Binda tried to convince Coppi that he had been delayed, and he succeeded in keeping Coppi in the race.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=159\u2013165}}\n\nIn the [[Alps]], Coppi recovered. In the sixteenth stage, Coppi escaped, and only Bartali followed him. It was Bartali's 35th birthday, and Coppi gave Bartali the stage victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclinghalloffame.com/riders/rider_bio.asp?rider_id=13|publisher=Cycling hall of fame|title=Rider biographies - Fausto Coppi|accessdate=20 February 2010}}</ref> After that stage, Bartali was first in the general classification, with Coppi in second place, 82 seconds behind.\nIn stage 17, Bartali and Coppi again were leading together. Around 40&nbsp;km into the stage, Bartali punctured. Coppi waited for Bartali, but when Bartali later fell and twisted his ankle, team leader Binda allowed Coppi to take  off alone.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> Coppi did so, won the stage, and decided the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1949/histoire.html|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|year=2009|accessdate=2 December 2009|title=The Tour - Year 1949|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716155341/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1949/histoire.html|archive-date=16 July 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThat seventeenth stage finished in the Italian town Aosta. Many Italians had come to see the Tour de France, to cheer on their Italian heroes Coppi and Bartali but also to express their anger against the French cyclists, specifically [[Jean Robic]], who had said in an interview that he could beat those Italians easily. Insults were shouted against non-Italians in the Tour, and some windows of French cars were smashed. For safety, and because there were not enough telephone connections for the journalists, most Tour officials and journalists decided to spend the night in Switzerland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ddd:010886606:mpeg21:a0054|title=De ronde van Frankrijk: wanorderlijke taferelen|trans-title=Tour de France: disorderly scenes|date=21 July 1949|accessdate=19 April 2017|publisher=Delpher|work=Nieuwsblad van het Noorden|page=3|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Tour returned to France in the nineteenth stage to Colmar, some French spectators took revenge by throwing tomatoes and rocks towards the Italian cyclists and followers. The organisation apologised for this behavior, and the Italian cyclists accepted this apology.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=http://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ddd:011239483:mpeg21:a0106|title=De Fransen: oog om oog, tand om tand|trans-title=The French: eye for an eye, tooth for a tooth|date=23 July 1949|access-date=5 March 2018|via=[[Delpher]]|newspaper=[[De Gooi- en Eemlander]]|page=5|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\nIn the rest of the race, Coppi's lead was not endangered; Coppi won the mountain time trial in stage 20, and won the Tour with a margin of more than ten minutes over Bartali.\n\n==Classification leadership and minor prizes==\n\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish each stage was recorded, and these times were added together for the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]]. If a cyclist had received a time bonus, it was subtracted from this total; all time penalties were added to this total. The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=452\u2013453}} Of the 120 cyclists, 55 finished the race.\n\nPoints for the [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]] were earned by reaching the mountain tops first.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}} There were two types of mountain tops: the hardest ones, in category 1, gave 10 points to the first cyclist, the easier ones, in category 2, gave 5 points to the first cyclist, and the easiest ones, in category 3, gave 3 points.\n\nThe [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]] was calculated by adding the times in the general classification of the best three cyclists per team.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=455}} The Italy Cadets and Switzerland finished with two cyclists each, so they were not eligible for this classification.\n\nThe [[Souvenir Henri Desgrange]] was given in honour of Tour founder [[Henri Desgrange]] to the first rider to pass a point by his final residence, the \"Villa Mia\" in Beauvallon, [[Grimaud, Var|Grimaud]], on the [[French Riviera]].<ref name=\"volkskrant-shd\">{{cite news|title=Apo Lazarid\u00e8s verovert 12 minuten op Bartali en Coppi|trans-title=Apo Lazarid\u00e8s conquers 12 minutes on Bartali and Coppi|url=https://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ABCDDD:010880442:mpeg21:p003|work=[[De Volkskrant]]|date=18 July 1949|page=3|language=Dutch|via=[[Delpher]]}}</ref>{{sfn|Seray|Lablaine|2006|p=84}} This prize was won by [[Paul Giguet]] on stage 15.<ref name=\"volkskrant-shd\" /> The special award for the best regional rider was won by third-placed [[Jacques Marinelli]].{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=40}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:smaller; clear:both;\"\n|+Classification leadership by stage<ref name=\"tdf-statistics\">{{cite web|last=van den Akker|first=Pieter|title=Informatie over de Tour de France van 1949|trans-title=Information about the Tour de France from 1949|url=http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1949|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302050043/http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1949|archivedate=2 March 2019|language=Dutch|website=TourDeFranceStatistieken.nl|accessdate=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1%;\"| Stage\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| Winner\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|25px|alt=|link=]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|Mountains classification]]{{efn|name=mountains-jersey|No jersey was awarded to the leader of the mountains classification until a white jersey with red [[polka dot]]s was introduced in [[1975 Tour de France|1975]].{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}}}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Team classification in the Tour de France|Team classification]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| [[Marcel Dussault]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Marcel Dussault]]\n| rowspan=\"10\"| ''no award''\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Belgium\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| [[Roger Lambrecht]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Roger Lambrecht]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| [[Norbert Callens]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Norbert Callens]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| [[Lucien Teisseire]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"6\"| [[Jacques Marinelli]]\n| France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]\n| rowspan=\"6\"| \u00cele-de-France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| [[Adolphe Deledda]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| [[Fausto Coppi]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| [[Guy Lap\u00e9bie]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| [[Louis Caput]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| [[Fiorenzo Magni]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"6\"| [[Fiorenzo Magni]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| [[Jean Robic]]\n| rowspan=\"11\"| [[Fausto Coppi]]\n| rowspan=\"4\"| Italy\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| [[Rik Van Steenbergen]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n| [[Emile Id\u00e9e]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n| [[Jean Goldschmidt]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n| [[D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Keteleer]]\n| \u00cele-de-France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| rowspan=\"6\"| Italy\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 17\n| [[Fausto Coppi]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"5\"| [[Fausto Coppi]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 18\n| [[Vincenzo Rossello]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 19\n| [[Rapha\u00ebl G\u00e9miniani]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 20\n| [[Fausto Coppi]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 21\n| [[Rik Van Steenbergen]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Final\n! style=\"background:#FFDB00;\"|[[Fausto Coppi]]\n! [[Fausto Coppi]]\n! Italy\n|}\n\n==Final standings==\n\n===General classification===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:38em;margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1949\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fausto Coppi]]|ITA}} || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" |   149h 40' 49\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}} || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 10' 55\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jacques Marinelli]]|FRA}} || \u00cele-de-France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 25' 13\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Robic]]|FRA}} || West/North || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 34' 28\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Dupont]]|BEL}} || Belgium Aiglons || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 38' 59\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fiorenzo Magni]]|ITA}} || Italy Cadets || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 42' 10\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Stan Ockers]]|BEL}} || Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 44' 35\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Goldschmit]]|LUX}} || Luxembourg || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 47' 24\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Apo Lazarid\u00e8s]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 52' 28\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Cogan]]|FRA}} || West/North || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 08' 55\"\n|}\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed wikitable\" style=\"width:38em;margin-top:-1px;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\" | Final general classification (11\u201355)\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |11\n| {{flagathlete|[[Roger Lambrecht]]|BEL}} || Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 17' 21\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |12\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gino Sciardis]]|ITA}} || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 22' 01\