|}\n\n{{columns-start}}\n\n===Mountains classification===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final mountains classification (1\u20139)<ref>{{cite news|title=Coppi \u00e8 il drappo svettante di una baniera impugnata da Bartali|trans-title=Coppi and the towering drape of a basket held by Bartali|url=http://dlib.coninet.it/bookreader.php?&c=1&f=7610|work=[[Corriere dello Sport]]|date=25 July 1949|page=2|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004134838/http://dlib.coninet.it/bookreader.php?&c=1&f=7610|archive-date=10 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fausto Coppi]]|ITA}} || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 81\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}} || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 68\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Robic]]|FRA}} || West/North || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 64\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Apo Lazarid\u00e8s]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 48\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 29\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Stan Ockers]]|BEL}} || Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 22\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\" |7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Giuseppe Tacca]]|FRA}} || \u00cele-de-France || style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"2\" | 16\n|-\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jacques Marinelli]]|FRA}} || \u00cele-de-France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\" |9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Rapha\u00ebl G\u00e9miniani]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" rowspan=\"2\" | 14\n|-\n| {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Brul\u00e9 (cyclist)|Andr\u00e9 Brul\u00e9]]|FRA}} || \u00cele-de-France\n|}\n\n{{column}}\n\n===Team classification===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final team classification<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1949.php|first=Tom|last=James|date=14 August 2003|accessdate=2 December 2009|publisher=Veloarchive|title=1949: Coppi's double}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/HEM/1949/07/25/MD19490725-003.pdf|date=25 July 1947|language=Spanish|title=Termin\u00f3 la Vuelta a Francia|work=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|page=3|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312165615/http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/HEM/1949/07/25/MD19490725-003.pdf|archive-date=12 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 450h 35' 23\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| West/North || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 10' 21\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| Luxembourg || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 18' 16\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 33' 08\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| \u00cele-de-France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 41' 36\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 00' 13\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| Belgium Aiglons || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 21' 25\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| South-East || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 5h 49' 25\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| Centre/South-West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 8h 15' 30\"\n|}\n\n{{columns-end}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nAs Coppi had also won the [[1949 Giro d'Italia]], he became the first person to achieve the Giro-Tour double.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n\nAfter the unrest in Aosta and Colmar, there were doubts if the Italian cyclists would return in 1950, and if that Tour should pass through Italy again.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=http://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ddd:011239483:mpeg21:a0103|title=Geminiani en Goasmat brachten vuur in etappe naar Colmar|trans-title=Geminiani and Goasmat put fire into the stage to Colmar|date=23 July 1949|accessdate=5 March 2018|via=Delpher|newspaper=[[De Gooi- en Eemlander]]|page=5|language=Dutch}}</ref> At the start of the [[1950 Tour de France]], the Italian team was present and the Tour was scheduled to go through Italy, but after further incidents the Italian team left the race, and the stage through Italy was rerouted.\n\nCoppi would go on to repeat the Giro-Tour double in 1952.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Seray|first1=Jacques|last2=Lablaine|first2=Jacques|author-link1=:fr:Jacques Seray|title=Henri Desgrange, l'homme qui cr\u00e9a le Tour de France|trans-title=Henri Desgrange, the man who created the Tour de France|language=French|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EKgTAQAAIAAJ|publisher=Editions Cristel|location=Saint-Malo, France|year=2006|isbn=978-2-84421-042-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Nauright|first1=John|last2=Parrish|first2=Charles|title=Sports Around the World: History, Culture, and Practice|volume=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IkLYDgTnMxEC|year=2012|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn=978-1-59884-300-2|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1949|1949 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1949 Tour de France|1|11|12|21}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n{{1949 Challenge Desgrange-Colombo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1949 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1949 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1949 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1949 in road cycling]]\n[[Category:June 1949 sports events|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1949 sports events|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:1949 Challenge Desgrange-Colombo|Tour de France]]\n", "name_user": "BaldBoris", "label": "safe", "comment": "notelist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1949_Tour_de_France"}
{"title_page": "1948 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1948 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1948.png\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1948 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting and finishing in Paris\n| image_alt          =\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 30 June \u2013 25 July\n| stages             = 21\n| distance           = 4922\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 145h 36' 56\"\n| first              = [[Gino Bartali]]\n| first_nat          = ITA\n| first_color        = yellow\n| first_team         = Italy\n| second             = [[Briek Schotte]]\n| second_nat         = BEL\n| second_team        = Belgium\n| third              = [[Guy Lap\u00e9bie]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| third_team         = Centre\u2013South-East\n| team               = Belgium\n| mountains          = [[Gino Bartali]]\n| mountains_nat      = ITA\n| mountains_team     = Italy\n| previous           = [[1947 Tour de France|1947]]\n| next               = [[1949 Tour de France|1949]]\n}}\nThe '''1948 Tour de France''' was the 35th edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place from 30 June to 25 July. It consisted of 21 stages over {{convert|4922|km|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe race was won by Italian cyclist [[Gino Bartali]], who had also won the Tour de France in 1938. Bartali had almost given up during the race, but drew inspiration from a phone call from the Italian prime minister, who asked him to win the Tour de France to prevent civil unrest in Italy after assassination attempt against  [[Palmiro Togliatti|Togliatti]]. Bartali also won the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]], while the [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]] was won by the Belgian team.\n\n==Changes from the previous Tour==\nThe prize for wearing the yellow jersey was introduced in 1948,<ref name=\"mdc1948\"/> sponsored by Les Laines, a French wool company.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=49}} In 1947, the media had complained that too many cyclists reached the end of the race, so the race was no longer heroic; this may have motivated a new rule between the third and the eighteenth stage, the rider last in the general classification was eliminated;<ref name=\"mdc1948\"/>{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=115}} Where as the 1947 Tour de France had been France-centred, the 1948 race became a more cosmopolitan race.{{sfn|Dauncey|Hare|2003|p=213}}\n\nThe Tour visited the [[Saar (protectorate)|Saar protectorate]] for the first time when the 18th stage passed [[Saarbr\u00fccken]] and [[Saarlouis]]. A second visit took place in [[1953 Tour de France|1953]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saar-nostalgie.de/Tour_de_France.htm |title=Die Tour de France im Saarland |publisher=Saar-Nostalgie |year=2013 |accessdate=3 July 2013 |language=German |author=Rainer Freyer |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6HsSfuXuv?url=http://www.saar-nostalgie.de/Tour_de_France.htm |archivedate=5 July 2013 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nThe first live television broadcast from the Tour de France was in 1948,{{sfn|Dauncey|Hare|2003|p=132}} when the arrival at the velodrome of [[Parc des Princes]] was broadcast live.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=39}}\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1948 Tour de France}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | image1            = Gino Bartali, Tour de France 1950.jpg\n | width1            = 146\n | image2            = Fausto Coppi, Tour de France 1952 01 (cropped).jpg\n | width2            = 160\n | footer            = [[Gino Bartali]] ''(left, pictured at the [[1950 Tour de France|1950 Tour]])'' and [[Fausto Coppi]] ''(right, pictured at the [[1952 Tour de France|1952 Tour]])''\n}}\nAs was the custom since the [[1930 Tour de France]], the 1948 Tour de France was contested by national and regional teams.\n\nAfter there had not been an official Italian team allowed in the previous edition, the Italians were back. The Italian cyclists were divided between [[Gino Bartali]] and [[Fausto Coppi]]. Both argued in the preparation of the race about who would be the team leader. The Tour organisation wanted to have both cyclists in the race, so they allowed the Italians and Belgians to enter a second team.{{sfn|Maso|2003|p=37}} In the end, Coppi refused to participate, and Bartali became the team leader.{{sfn|Ligget|Raia|Lewis|2005|p=213}} The organisation still allowed the Italians and Belgians to enter a second team, but they were to be composed of young cyclists, and were named the Italy Cadets and the Belgium Aiglons.{{sfn|Maso|2003|p=37}}\n\nThe Tour organisation invited the Swiss to send a team, as they wanted [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]], the winner of the 1948 [[Tour de Suisse]], in the race. K\u00fcbler refused this because he could earn more money in other races. When the brothers [[Georges Aeschlimann|Georges]] and [[Roger Aeschlimann]] announced that they wanted to join the race, they were quickly accepted, especially because they were from Lausanne, where the Tour would pass through. They were put in a team with eight non-French cyclists living in France, and were named the Internationals.{{sfn|Maso|2003|p=26}}\n\nTwelve teams of ten cyclists entered the race, consisting of 60 French cyclists, 24 Italian, 22 Belgian, 6 Dutch, 4 Luxembourgian, 2 Swiss, 1 Polish and 1 Algerian cyclist.<ref name=\"tgv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tour-giro-vuelta.net|title=Tour-Giro-Vuelta|work=www.tour-giro-vuelta.net|accessdate=30 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe teams entering the race were:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Belgium\n* Netherlands/Luxembourg\n* Internationals\n* Italy\n* France\n* Belgium Aiglons\n* Italy Cadets\n* Centre/South-West\n* \u00cele-de-France/North-East\n* West\n* Paris\n* South-East\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Route and stages==\n\nBartali's three stage wins in a row was the last time that happened, until [[Mario Cipollini]] achieved four in a row in [[1999 Tour de France|1999]].<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> There were five rest days, in Biarritz, Toulouse, Cannes, Aix-les-Bains and Mulhouse.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=39}} The [[List of highest points reached in the Tour de France|highest point of elevation in the race]] was {{convert|2556|m|ft|abbr=on}} at the summit tunnel of the [[Col du Galibier]] mountain pass on stage 14.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|pp=177\u2013178}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Il 35\u00ba Giro di Francia si Metter\u00e0 in moto domani|trans-title=The 35th Tour of France will start tomorrow|url=http://dlib.coninet.it/bookreader.php?&f=6074|work=[[Corriere dello Sport]]|date=29 June 1948|page=1|language=Italian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221002601/http://dlib.coninet.it/bookreader.php?&f=6074|archive-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1948\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1948.php|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=35\u00e8me Tour de France 1948|language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120828121950/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1948.php|archive-date=28 August 2012|access-date=26 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=39}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1948 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |author=Arian Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |accessdate=30 November 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hQnRPAvL?url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archivedate=10 June 2009 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 30 June\n| [[Paris]] to [[Trouville-sur-Mer|Trouville]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|237|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1 July\n| [[Trouville-sur-Mer|Trouville]] to [[Dinard]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|259|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Vincenzo Rossello]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2 July\n| [[Dinard]] to [[Nantes]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|251|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Guy Lap\u00e9bie]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3 July\n| [[Nantes]] to [[La Rochelle]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|166|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Jacques Pras]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4 July\n| [[La Rochelle]] to [[Bordeaux]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|262|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Raoul Remy]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5 July\n| [[Bordeaux]] to [[Biarritz]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|244|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Louison Bobet]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Biarritz]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7 July\n| [[Biarritz]] to [[Lourdes]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|219|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8 July\n| [[Lourdes]] to [[Toulouse]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|261|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Toulouse]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 10 July\n| [[Toulouse]] to [[Montpellier]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|246|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Raymond Impanis]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |10\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 July\n| [[Montpellier]] to [[Marseille]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|248|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Raymond Impanis]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |11\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12 July\n| [[Marseille]] to [[Sanremo]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|245|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Sciardis]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |12\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13 July\n| [[Sanremo]] to [[Cannes]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|170|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Louison Bobet]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 14 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Cannes]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |13\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 15 July\n| [[Cannes]] to [[Brian\u00e7on]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|274|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |14\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 July\n| [[Brian\u00e7on]] to [[Aix-les-Bains]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|263|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Aix-les-Bains]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |15\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 18 July\n| [[Aix-les-Bains]] to [[Lausanne]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|256|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |16\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 19 July\n| [[Lausanne]] to [[Mulhouse]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|243|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Edward Van Dijck]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Mulhouse]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |17\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 21 July\n| [[Mulhouse]] to [[Strasbourg]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|120|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] ||{{flagathlete|[[Roger Lambrecht]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |18\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 22 July\n| [[Strasbourg]] to [[Metz]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|195|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Giovanni Corrieri]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |19\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 23 July\n| [[Metz]] to [[Li\u00e8ge]] (Belgium)|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|249|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |20\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 24 July\n| [[Li\u00e8ge]] (Belgium) to [[Roubaix]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|228|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Bernard Gauthier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |21\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 25 July\n| [[Roubaix]] to [[Paris]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|286|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Giovanni Corrieri]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4922|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=109}}\n|}\n\n==Race overview==\n[[File:Tourde France 1948 margin.svg|thumb|alt=Graph with \"Margin\" on the y-axis and \"Stage\" on the x-axis. The x-axis goes from 1 to 21, and the graph starts at stage 1 at 0:00, rises to above 20:00 but returns to 0:00 at stage 13.|The margin between Gino Bartali and the leader of the race in the 1948 Tour de France. After the twelfth stage, the margin reached it maximum at 21:28, but after that it quickly went down.]]\nAs the Italian team had not entered the Tours de France of 1939 and 1947, it was the first Tour de France for Bartali since his victory ten years before in 1938. His results in the [[Giro d'Italia]] had not been well, and it was not thought that Bartali could compete for the win.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1948.php|publisher=Veloarchive|author=Tom James|date=15 August 2003|accessdate=2 December 2009|title=1948: Bartali saves Italy}}</ref>\n\nBartali however won the sprint in the first stage, and thanks to the bonification of one minute for the winner, he was leading the race. After that, the Italian team took a low profile in the race.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\nIn the second stage, Bartali lost the lead already; although his teammate [[Vincenzo Rossello]] won the stage, Belgian [[Jan Engels]] took over the yellow jersey.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=56}}\n\nIn the third stage, a group escaped and built up a lead of almost 14 minutes. Among that group was [[Louison Bobet]], and as he was the best-placed cyclist in that group he became the next leader. Also in that group was [[Roger Lambrecht]]; when Lambrecht again was able to be in the first group in the fourth stage, he took the lead, becoming the fourth rider in four stages to don the yellow jersey. Lambrecht kept it in the next stage, but after Bobet won the sixth stage, Bobet took back the lead, and the yellow jersey made him confident.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=56}} In the Pyren\u00e9es, Bartali won both stages in a sprint, but Bobet was near and became the hero of the French spectators.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=56}}\n\nAfter the ninth stage, Bobet had built up a lead of more than nine minutes. In the tenth stage, he lost time, and Belgian cyclist [[Roger Lambrecht]] reduced the margin to 29 seconds. After the eleventh stage, Bobet was still in the lead, but was having problems, and after he fainted at the finish, he wanted to give up. After a meal, massage and sleeping, he changed his mind, and won the twelfth stage.<ref name=\"letour.fr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1948/histoire.html|title=The Tour - Year 1948|publisher=letour.fr|author=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=2 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225041159/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1948/histoire.html|archive-date=25 February 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter the twelfth stage, Bartali was 20 minutes behind. Bartali thought about quitting the tour, but was persuaded to race on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://outside.away.com/outside/events/column/col0705.html|title=Looking back: Tour de France 1948|author=Bill Henderson|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=2 December 2009|publisher=away.com}}</ref> That night, Bartali received a phone call while he was in bed. [[Alcide De Gasperi]], prime minister of Italy, from the [[Christian Democracy (Italy)|Christian Democratic party]], told him that a few days earlier [[Palmiro Togliatti]], leader of the [[Italian Communist Party]], had been shot, and Italy might be on the edge of a civil war. De Gasperi asked Bartali to do his best to win a stage, because the sport news might distract people from the politics. Bartali replied that he would do better, and win the race.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\nThe next day, Bartali won stage 13 with a large margin. In the general classification, he jumped to second place, trailing by only 66 seconds. In the fourteenth stage, Bartali and Bobet rode together over the Galibier and the Croix de Fer, but Bartali had been saving his energy, and left Bobet and every body else behind on the Col de Porte. Bartali won again, and took over the yellow jersey as leader of the general classification. Bobet was now in second place, eight minutes behind. The next stage, stage 15, was also won by Bartali.\nThe sixteenth stage was not won by Bartali, but because his direct competitors lost time, he increased his lead to 32 minutes.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> Bartali lost minutes in the time trial in stage 17, but his lead was never endangered.\n\nWith each stage win of Bartali (seven in total), the Italian excitement about the Tour de France increased, and the political tensions quieted.<ref name=\"revealed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1948.htm|title=Gino \"the Pious,\" an Inspirational Win|author=Barry Boyce|year=2004|accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Classification leadership and minor prizes==\n\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish each stage was recorded, and these times were added together for the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]]. If a cyclist had received a time bonus, it was subtracted from this total; all time penalties were added to this total. The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=452\u2013453}} The budget of the Tour de France in 1948 was 45 million Francs, from which one third was provided by private enterprises.<ref>Dauncey, p.110</ref> In total, 7 million Francs of prizes were awarded in the 1948 Tour de France. Of these, 600.000 Francs were given to Bartali for winning the general classification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1948/index.html|title=l'Historique du Tour de France, Ann\u00e9e 1948|publisher=letour.fr|author=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=2 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715154737/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1948/index.html|archive-date=15 July 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bartali is the only cyclist to win two Tours de France ten years apart.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=156\u2013159}} Of the 120 cyclists, 44 finished the race.\n\nPoints for the [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]] were earned by reaching the mountain tops first.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}} There were two types of mountain tops: the hardest ones, in category A, gave 10 points to the first cyclist, the easier ones, in category B, gave 5 points to the first cyclist.\n\nThe [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]] was calculated by adding the times in the general classification of the best three cyclists per team.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=455}}\n\nThe [[Souvenir Henri Desgrange]] was given in honour of Tour founder [[Henri Desgrange]] in the opening few kilometres of stage 1 at the summit of the [[:fr:Avenue des \u00c9tats-Unis (Versailles)|C\u00f4te de Picardie]] in [[Versailles, Yvelines|Versailles]], Paris.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.eu/eta_tdf_1947_1949/tdf1948_1.php|work=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=35\u00e8me Tour de France 1948 - 1\u00e8re \u00e9tape|trans-title=35th Tour de France 1948 - 1st stage|language=French|access-date=19 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191202164631/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.eu/eta_tdf_1947_1949/tdf1948_1.php|archive-date=2 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"1948-parool\">{{cite news|title=Tour de France begonnen|trans-title=Tour de France begins|url=https://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ABCDDD:010830971:mpeg21:p003|work=[[Het Parool]]|date=30 June 1948|page=3|language=Dutch|via=[[Delpher]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Versailles: les statues de La Fayette et Pershing inaugur\u00e9es |trans-title=Versailles: La Fayette and Pershing statues inaugurated |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/yvelines-78/versailles-78000/versailles-les-statues-de-la-fayette-et-pershing-inaugurees-05-10-2017-7309599.php |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=[[Le Parisien]] |date=5 October 2017 |language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191202164707/http://www.leparisien.fr/yvelines-78/versailles-78000/versailles-les-statues-de-la-fayette-et-pershing-inaugurees-05-10-2017-7309599.php|archive-date=2 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> This prize was won by [[Roger Lambrecht]].<ref name=\"1948-parool\" /> The Tour de France in 1948 for the first time had a special award for the best regional rider.<ref name=\"letour.fr\"/> This was won by third-placed [[Guy Lap\u00e9bie]].{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=39}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:smaller; clear:both;\"\n|+Classification leadership by stage<ref name=\"tdf-statistics\">{{cite web|last=van den Akker|first=Pieter|title=Informatie over de Tour de France van 1948|trans-title=Information about the Tour de France from 1948|url=http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1948|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302050036/http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1948|archivedate=2 March 2019|language=Dutch|website=TourDeFranceStatistieken.nl|accessdate=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1%;\"| Stage\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| Winner\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|25px|alt=|link=]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|Mountains classification]]{{refn|No jersey was awarded to the leader of the mountains classification until a white jersey with red [[polka dot]]s was introduced in 1975.<ref name=\"jerseys\">{{cite news|last=Cunningham|first=Josh|title=History of the Tour de France jerseys|url=http://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/1409/history-of-the-tour-de-france-jerseys|accessdate=2 October 2016|work=Cyclist|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|date=4 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026180408/http://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/1409/history-of-the-tour-de-france-jerseys|archive-date=26 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>|group=\"n\"|name=\"mountains-jersey\"}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Team classification in the Tour de France|Team classification]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| rowspan=\"6\"| ''no award''\n| Belgium\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| [[Vincenzo Rossello]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Jan Engels]]\n| Belgium B\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| [[Guy Lap\u00e9bie]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Louison Bobet]]\n| France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| [[Jacques Pras]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Roger Lambrecht]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Internationals\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| [[Raoul Remy]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| [[Louison Bobet]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"8\"| [[Louison Bobet]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| [[Bernard Gauthier]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"| France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[Jean Robic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| [[Raymond Impanis]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| [[Raymond Impanis]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Internationals\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| [[Gino Sciardis]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| [[Louison Bobet]]\n| rowspan=\"5\"| France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"8\"| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[Gino Bartali]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n| [[Gino 