stage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6 July\n| [[Digne]] to [[Nice]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|255|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Fermo Camellini]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Nice]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8 July\n| [[Nice]] to [[Marseille]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|230|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[\u00c9douard Fachleitner]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9 July\n| [[Marseille]] to [[Montpellier]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|165|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Henri Massal]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 10 July\n| [[Montpellier]] to [[Carcassonne]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|172|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Lucien Teisseire]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 14|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 July\n| [[Carcassonne]] to [[Luchon]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|253|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Albert Bourlon]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Luchon]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 15|15]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13 July\n| [[Luchon]] to [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|195|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) ||{{flagathlete|[[Jean Robic]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 16|16]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 14 July\n| [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]] to [[Bordeaux]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|195|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Giuseppe Tacca]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 17|17]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 15 July\n| [[Bordeaux]] to [[Les Sables-d'Olonne]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|272|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[\u00c9loi Tassin]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 18|18]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 July\n| [[Les Sables-d'Olonne]] to [[Vannes]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|236|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Pietro Tarchini]]|SUI}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Vannes]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 19|19]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 18 July\n| [[Vannes]] to [[Saint-Brieuc]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|139|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] ||{{flagathlete|[[Raymond Impanis]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 20|20]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 19 July\n| [[Saint-Brieuc]] to [[Caen]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|235|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Maurice Diot]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 21|21]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 July\n| [[Caen]] to [[Paris]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|257|km|0|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage ||{{flagathlete|[[Briek Schotte]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4642|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n==Race overview==\n{{main|1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11|1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21}}\n[[File:Nummer een en twee komen binnen, Ferdi K\u00fcbler (Zwitserland) gevolgd door Mah\u00e9 (F, Bestanddeelnr 902-2379.jpg|thumb|left|[[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]] crossing the finish line in [[Lille]] ahead of [[Andr\u00e9 Mah\u00e9]] to win the opening stage]]\nAfter [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]] had won the first stage, [[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]] took the lead by winning the second stage. After the third stage only [[Aldo Ronconi]] was within 90 seconds of Vietto, and the third man in the general classification was already more than eight minutes behind.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://veloarchive.com/races/tour/1947.php|title=1947: Robic snatches it at the death|first=Tom|last=James|date=15 August 2003|accessdate=22 February 2010|publisher=Veloarchive}}</ref>\n\nIn the seventh stage, when the Alps mountains were climbed, Ronconi took over the lead, but two stages later Vietto took back the lead, helped by [[Apo Lazarides]].</ref>{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=54}}\n\n[[Jean Robic]] had lost six minutes in that ninth stage, and lost more time in the tenth stage. He was already more than 25 minutes behind, and was no longer considered a favourite, but Robic was convinced that he would win the Tour.{{sfn|Dauncey|Hare|2003|p=54}}\n\nIn the fourteenth stage, [[Albert Bourlon]] escaped directly after the start. He stayed away until the end of the stage, {{convert|253|km|mi|abbr=on}} later. This is the longest escape in the Tour de France after the second World War.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n\nIn the fifteenth stage, Robic escaped in the Pyr\u00e9nees, and beat the other by more than ten minutes. Because of the time bonuses for reaching the mountain tops first, he even won back more than fifteen minutes.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=151\u2013156}} In the general classification, Robic rose to fifth place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1947_15.php|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=34\u00e8me Tour de France 1947 - 15\u00e8me \u00e9tape|language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302183704/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1947_15.php|archive-date=2 March 2012|access-date=26 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nWith only three stages to go in the Tour, Vietto was still in the lead, 94 seconds ahead of [[Pierre Brambilla]]. The nineteenth stage was an [[individual time trial]], the longest in Tour history.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> In that stage, Vietto lost considerable time, and Brambilla took over the lead in the general classification.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> Vietto performed worse than expected; there was speculation about why he performed so badly, and some said it was because of the motorcycle accident of a friend, while others said it was because he drank a bottle of cider during the time trial.<ref name=\"letour.fr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1947/histoire.html|title=The Tour - Year 1947|author=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|access-date=20 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717054428/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1947/histoire.html|archive-date=17 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\"\n|+General classification before stage 21<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1947_20.php|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=34\u00e8me Tour de France 1947 - 20\u00e9me \u00e8tape|language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302183706/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1947_20.php|archive-date=2 March 2012|access-date=26 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!!Cyclist!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n|{{flagathlete|[[Pierre Brambilla]]|ITA}} || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 140h 44' 38\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Aldo Ronconi]]|ITA}} || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 53\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Robic]]|FRA}} || West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2' 58\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 5' 16\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[\u00c9douard Fachleitner]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 6' 56\"\n|}\nThe last stage was flat, which makes it hard for escapers to win time.<ref name=\"mdc21etape\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1947_21.php|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=34\u00e8me Tour de France 1947 - 21\u00e8me \u00e9tape|language=French|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302183707/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1947_21.php|archive-date=2 March 2012|access-date=26 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> In that last stage, there was a hilltop prime, where money could be won by the first cyclist that passed. Although a group had already passed that hill, Robic was not aware of this, and sprinted for this prime.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> When he reached the top, Brambilla had been dropped. Robic and Fachleitner, fifth in the general classification, started to work together, and left Brambilla and Ronconi minutes behind. Around 140&nbsp;km before the finish, they were three minutes ahead of Brambilla, which made Robic the virtual leader of the race. At that point Robic told Fachleitner: \"You can not win the Tour, because I will not let you escape. If you ride with me, I will pay you 100.000 Francs.\"<ref name=\"mdc21etape\"/>\n\nWhen they reached Paris, they had won 13 minutes on them, enough to make Robic the winner of the Tour de France.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n\n==Classification leadership and minor prizes==\n\nThe cyclist to reach the finish in the least time was the winner of the stage. The time that each cyclist required to finish the stage was recorded. For the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], these times were added together. If a cyclist had received a time bonus, it was subtracted from this total; all time penalties were added to this total. The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=452\u2013453}} With his victory, Robic won 500.000 francs. Additionally, future exhibitions and endorsements due to the Tour victory would give him another 3 to 4 million francs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,855841,00.html|publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=14 October 2009|date=4 August 1947|title=Sport: Derby on Wheels}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, there was the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]], which did not have a jersey associated with it in 1947.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}} Sixteen mountains were selected by the Tour organisation, divided in two classes.<ref name=\"mdc1947\"/> In the first-class mountains, the ten first cyclists received points, with 10 points for the first, 9 for the second, and so forth, to 1 point for the tenth. In the second-class mountains, only the first five cyclists received points, 5 for the first one to 1 for the fifth one. The mountains classification was won by [[Pierre Brambilla]].\n\nThe [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]] was calculated in 1947 by adding up the times of the best three cyclists of a team; the team with the least time was the winner.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=455}}\n\nThe [[Souvenir Henri Desgrange]] was given in honour of Tour founder [[Henri Desgrange]] to the first rider to pass a point by his final residence, the \"Villa Mia\" in Beauvallon, [[Grimaud, Var|Grimaud]], on the [[French Riviera]].<ref name=\"volkskrant-shd\">{{cite news|title=Fachleitner schudde allen van zijn wiel|trans-title=Fachleitner shook everyone's wheel|url=https://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ABCDDD:010936294:mpeg21:p002|work=[[De Volkskrant]]|date=9 July 1947|page=2|language=Dutch|via=[[Delpher]]}}</ref>{{sfn|Seray|Lablaine|2006|p=84}} This prize was won by [[Raymond Impanis]] on stage 11.<ref name=\"volkskrant-shd\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:smaller; clear:both;\"\n|+Classification leadership by stage<ref name=\"tdf-statistics\">{{cite web|last=van den Akker|first=Pieter|title=Informatie over de Tour de France van 1947|trans-title=Information about the Tour de France from 1947|url=http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1947|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302050025/http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1947|archive-date=2 March 2019|language=Dutch|website=TourDeFranceStatistieken.nl|access-date=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1%;\"| Stage\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| Winner\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|25px|alt=|link=]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|Mountains classification]]{{refn|No jersey was awarded to the leader of the mountains classification until a white jersey with red [[polka dot]]s was introduced in [[1975 Tour de France|1975]].{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}}|group=\"n\"|name=\"mountains-jersey\"}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Team classification in the Tour de France|Team classification]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 1|1]]\n| [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]\n| rowspan=\"6\"| ''no award''\n| France-West\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 2|2]]\n| [[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"5\"| [[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]]\n| Belgium\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 3|3]]\n| [[Aldo Ronconi]]\n| rowspan=\"10\"| Italy\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 4|4]]\n| [[Jean Robic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 5|5]]\n| [[Ferdinand K\u00fcbler]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 6|6]]\n| [[Lucien Teisseire]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 7|7]]\n| [[Jean Robic]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Aldo Ronconi]]\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 8|8]]\n| [[Fermo Camellini]]\n| [[Fermo Camellini]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 9|9]]\n| [[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"10\"| [[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]]\n| rowspan=\"6\"| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 10|10]]\n| [[Fermo Camellini]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 11|11]]\n| [[\u00c9douard Fachleitner]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 12|12]]\n| [[Henri Massal]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 13|13]]\n| [[Lucien Teisseire]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"| France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 14|14]]\n| [[Albert Bourlon]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 15|15]]\n| [[Jean Robic]]\n| rowspan=\"7\"| [[Pierre Brambilla]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 16|16]]\n| [[Giuseppe Tacca]]\n| rowspan=\"6\"| Italy\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 17|17]]\n| [[\u00c9loi Tassin]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 18|18]]\n| [[Pietro Tarchini]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 19|19]]\n| [[Raymond Impanis]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Pierre Brambilla]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 20|20]]\n| [[Maurice Diot]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1947 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 21|21]]\n| [[Briek Schotte]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Jean Robic]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Final\n! style=\"background:#FFDB00;\"|[[Jean Robic]]\n! [[Pierre Brambilla]]\n! Italy\n|}\n\n==Final standings==\n\n===General classification===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:42em;margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1947\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Robic]]|FRA}} || West || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 148h 11' 25\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[\u00c9douard Fachleitner]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3' 58\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Brambilla]]|ITA}} || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 10' 07\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Aldo Ronconi]]|ITA}} || Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 11' 00\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 15' 23\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Raymond Impan