0136\n|match_VIF_SFK=4\u20130\n|match_VIF_VIK=1\u20132\n\n|update= \n|source=[http://www.nifs.no/grid.php?land=1&t=5&u=9 NIFS.no] \n}}\n\n==Season statistics==\n===Top scorer===\n*[[Leif Eriksen]], [[V\u00e5lerenga Fotball|V\u00e5lerengen]] \u2013 16 goals\n\n===Attendances===\n{{fb a header}}\n{{fb a2 team|p=1 |t=[[SK Brann|Brann]]|s=140918|h=20897 |l=10750 |a=15658}}\n{{fb a2 team|p=2 |t=[[V\u00e5lerenga Fotball|V\u00e5lerengen]]|s=88301 |h=16600 |l=4973 |a=9811}}\n{{fb a2 team|p=3 |t=[[Skeid Fotball|Skeid]]|s=81597|h=18534 |l=4518 |a=9066}}\n{{fb a2 team|p=4 |t=[[Viking FK|Viking]]|s=67346|h=10600 |l=5000 |a=7483}}\n{{fb a2 team|p=5 |t=[[SFK Lyn|Lyn]]|s=67117|h=13947 |l=2684 |a=7457}}\n{{fb a2 team|p=6 |t=[[Fredrikstad FK|Fredrikstad]]|s=62889|h=12000 |l=4000 |a=6988}}\n{{fb a2 team|p=7 |t=[[Frigg Oslo FK|Frigg]]|s=59281|h=10855 |l=2519 |a=6587}}\n{{fb a2 team|p=8 |t=[[Steinkjer FK|Steinkjer]]|s=50313|h=8000 |l=3500 |a=5590}}\n{{fb a2 team|p=9|t=[[SK Gj\u00f8vik-Lyn|Gj\u00f8vik-Lyn]]|s=48037|h=10437|l=1500|a=5337}}\n{{fb a2 team|p=10|t=[[Sarpsborg FK]]|s=42569|h=7500 |l=1800 |a=4730}}\n{{fb a footer |s=708368|h=20897|l=1500|a=7871|source=[https://www.nifs.no/tilskuertall.php?land=1&t=5&fra=1963&til=1963&kamper=&sortering=avgt nifs.no]|date=May 2019}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.rsssf.no/stats/LeagueChamps.html Norway - List of final tables (RSSSF)]\n*[http://www.nifs.no Nifs.no (Norsk internasjonal fotballstatistikk)]\n\n{{Eliteserien}}\n{{1963 in Norwegian football}}\n{{1962\u201363 in European football (UEFA)}}\n{{1963\u201364 in European football (UEFA)}}\n\n[[Category:Eliteserien seasons]]\n[[Category:1962\u201363 in European association football leagues|Norway]]\n[[Category:1963\u201364 in European association football leagues|Norway]]\n[[Category:1963 in Norwegian football|1]]\n", "name_user": "Jolicnikola", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1963_1._divisjon"}
{"title_page": "1939 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1939 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1939.png\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1939 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = \n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 10\u201330 July\n| stages             = 18, including eight split stages\n| distance           = 4224\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 132h 03' 17\"\n| first              = [[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]]\n| first_nat          = BEL\n| first_color        = yellow\n| first_team         = Belgium\n| second             = [[Ren\u00e9 Vietto]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| second_team        = France\n| third              = [[Lucien Vlaemynck]]\n| third_nat          = BEL\n| third_team         = Belgium B\n| team               = Belgium B\n| mountains          = [[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]]\n| mountains_nat      = BEL\n| mountains_team     = Belgium\n| previous           = [[1938 Tour de France|1938]]\n| next               = [[1947 Tour de France|1947]]\n}}\nThe '''1939 Tour de France''' was the 33rd edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place from 10 to 30 July. The total distance was {{convert|4224|km|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nTaking place on the eve of [[World War II]], there was already much animosity in Europe. Italy, Germany and Spain all declined to send teams to the race, so the [[1938 Tour de France|1938]] Italian champion [[Gino Bartali]] would not be defending his title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enenvor.fr/eeo_revue/numero_2/velo/du_cliquetis_des_p%C3%A9dales_au_bruit_des_bottes.pdf|title=Du cliquetis des p\u00e9dales au bruit des bottes : un \u00e9t\u00e9 cycliste perturb\u00e9 en Bretagne (juillet-septembre 1939)|format=PDF|last=Evanno|first=Yves-Marie|publisher=En Envor, revue d'histoire contemporaine en Bretagne|year=2013|accessdate=16 December 2013|language=French|archiveurl=http://enenvor.fr/eeo_revue/numero_2/du_cliquetis_des_pedales_au_bruit_des_bottes.html|archivedate=1 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> To fill out the ranks, Belgium sent two teams, and France had five teams. This would be the final Tour for eight years, until [[1947 Tour de France|1947]].\n\nBetween the second and the seventh stage, the last rider in the general classification was eliminated.<ref name=\"mdc1939\"/>\n\nThe race was won by Belgian [[Sylv\u00e8re Maes]] who also won the mountains classification.\n\n==Changes from the previous Tour==\nFor the first time, a mountain time trial was scheduled: stage 16b.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=144\u2013147}}\nA rule was added to make it more difficult to finish the race: from the second stage to the seventh stage, the last rider in the classification was to be removed from the race.<ref name=\"mdc1939\"/>\n\nThe nutrition of the cyclists became more professional: cyclists were reporting that the use of vitamins increased their performance.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Applegate |first1=Elizabeth A.  |last2=Grivetti |first2=Louis E. |year= 1997 |title=Search for the Competitive Edge: A History of Dietary Fads and Supplements |journal=The Journal of Nutrition |volume=127|pmid=9164254 |issue=5 |pages=869S\u2013873S |url=http://jn.nutrition.org/cgi/content/full/127/5/869S |doi= }}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1939 Tour de France}}\n\nBecause Italy, Germany and Spain did not send teams,{{sfn|Bowen|2006|p=152}} the Tour organisation were short on participating cyclists. To solve this, they allowed Belgium to send two teams, and France to send four additional regional teams.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://veloarchive.com/races/tour/1939.php|title=1939: \"Le Roi Ren\u00e9\" and the regionals|author=James, Tom|date=15 August 2003|accessdate=25 January 2010|publisher=VeloArchive}}</ref>\n\nThe French cyclists had been successful in the 1930s, but their Tour winners were absent in 1939:\n1930 and 1932 winner [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]] had retired in 1938, as had 1931 and 1934 winner [[Antonin Magne]]; 1933 winner [[Georges Speicher]] did not ride, and 1937 winner [[Roger Lap\u00e9bie]] was injured. This all made the Belgian team favourite.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=144\u2013147}}\n\nThe teams entering the race were:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Belgium\n* Switzerland\n* Luxembourg\n* Netherlands\n* France\n* Belgium B\n* France North-East/\u00cele de France\n* France West\n* France South-West\n* France South-East\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Route and stages==\n\nThe [[List of highest points reached in the Tour de France|highest point of elevation in the race]] was {{convert|2770|m|ft|abbr=on}} at the summit of the [[Col de l'Iseran]] mountain pass on stage 16b.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=178}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Et voici, dix ans apres... Le Tour de France 1939|trans-title=And here, ten years later... The Tour de France 1939|url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k97984033/f3.item|work=[[:fr:Le Miroir des sports|Le Miroir des sports]]|date=11 July 1939|page=3|language=French|via=[[Gallica]]}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1939\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1939.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306131903/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1939.php|archive-date=6 March 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=33\u00e8me Tour de France 1939|language=French}}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=37}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1939 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |first=Arian |last=Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516071832/http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archivedate=16 May 2008 |url-status=live |accessdate=20 April 2009  }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type<ref group=\"n\">The icons shown here indicate whether the stage was run as a time trial, the stage was flat or the stage included mountains for the mountains classification. Stage 16b was a time trial that included a mountain.</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |10 July|| [[Paris]] to [[Caen]] || {{convert|215|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Am\u00e9d\u00e9e Fournier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 2a|2a]]\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |11 July|| [[Caen]] to [[Vire]] || {{convert|64|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] || {{flagathlete|[[Romain Maes]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 2b|2b]]\n| [[Vire]] to [[Rennes]] || {{convert|119|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[\u00c9loi Tassin]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |12 July|| [[Rennes]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]]|| {{convert|244|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Cloarec]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |13 July|| [[Brest Region|Brest]] to [[Lorient]] || {{convert|174|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Raymond Louviot]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1939 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |14 July|| [[Lorient]] to [[Nantes]] || {{convert|207|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg