le\"\n|+ Mountains in the mountains classification<ref name=\"mdc1938\"/>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|pp=175\u2013192}}\n|-\n!Stage!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!!Height!!Mountain range!! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n|Aubisque||{{convert|1709|m|ft}}||Pyrenees||Gino Bartali\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n|Tourmalet||{{convert|2115|m|ft}}||Pyrenees||Gino Bartali\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n|Aspin||{{convert|1489|m|ft}}||Pyrenees||Gino Bartali\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n|Peyresourde||{{convert|1569|m|ft}}||Pyrenees||F\u00e9licien Vervaecke\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n|Portet d'Aspet||{{convert|1069|m|ft}}||Pyrenees||Gino Bartali\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n|Braus||{{convert|1002|m|ft}}||Alps-Maritimes||Gino Bartali\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n|Allos||{{convert|2250|m|ft}}||Alps||Gino Bartali\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n|Vars||{{convert|2110|m|ft}}||Alps||Gino Bartali\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n|Izoard||{{convert|2361|m|ft}}||Alps||Gino Bartali\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n|Galibier||{{convert|2556|m|ft}}||Alps||Mario Vicini\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n|Iseran||{{convert|2770|m|ft}}||Alps||F\u00e9licien Vervaecke\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16\n|Faucille||{{convert|1320|m|ft}}||Alps||Gino Bartali\n|}\n\n{{column}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final mountains classification (1\u20135)<ref name=\"mdc1938\"/><ref name=\"tgv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tour-giro-vuelta.net/|title=Tour-Giro-Vuelta|accessdate=13 October 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gino Bartali]]|ITA|1861}}||Italy|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 107\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[F\u00e9licien Vervaecke]]|BEL}}||Belgium|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 79\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Edward Vissers]]|BEL}}||Belgium|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 76\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Dante Gianello]]|FRA}}||Bleuets|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 57\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Victor Cosson]]|FRA}}||France|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 55\n|}\n\n{{columns-end}}\n\n===Team classification===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final team classification (1\u20138)<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/><ref name=\"lc\">{{cite news|url=http://www.archiefleeuwardercourant.nl/site/article.do?code=LC&date=19380801&id=LC-19380801-12004|title=De Ronde van Frankrijk door Bartali gewonnen|date=1 August 1938|accessdate=13 October 2009|publisher=Leeuwarder Courant|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| Belgium || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 447h 10' 07\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 43' 29\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| Italy || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 44' 06\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| Luxembourg/Switzerland || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 02' 29\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| Cadets || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 11' 31\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| Spain/Netherlands || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 15' 29\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| Bleuets || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4h 04' 49\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| Germany || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 7h 05' 57\"\n|}\n\n==Aftermath==\n\nBecause of the political tensions in Europe before the Second World War, Italy did not send a team to the [[1939 Tour de France]], so Bartali was unable to defend his title.<ref name=\"mdc1939\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1939.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306131903/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1939.php|archive-date=6 March 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=33\u00e8me Tour de France 1939|language=French}}</ref> After the war, the Tour de France resumed in [[1947 Tour de France|1947]]. In [[1948 Tour de France|1948]], Bartali won his second Tour, becoming the first and so far only cyclist to win editions of the Tour de France ten years apart.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|pp=108\u2013109}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Moliterno|first=Gino|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6vVS_Y1mcIEC|title=Encyclopedia of Contemporary Italian Culture|year=2000|location=Boca Raton, FL|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|isbn=978-0-415-14584-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Nauright|first1=John|last2=Parrish|first2=Charles|title=Sports Around the World: History, Culture, and Practice|volume=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IkLYDgTnMxEC|year=2012|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn=978-1-59884-300-2|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1938|1938 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1938 Tour de France|1|10c|11|21}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1938 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1938 in road cycling]]\n[[Category:1938 in French sport]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year|1938]]\n[[Category:July 1938 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1938 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1938.png\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1938 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = \n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 5\u201331 July\n| stages             = 21, including five split stages\n| distance           = 4694\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 148h 29' 12\"\n| first              = [[Gino Bartali]]\n| first_nat          = ITA\n| first_natvar       = 1861\n| first_color        = yellow\n| first_team         = Italy\n| second             = [[F\u00e9licien Vervaecke]]\n| second_nat         = BEL\n| second_team        = Belgium\n| third              = [[Victor Cosson]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| third_team         = France\n| team               = Belgium\n| mountains          = [[Gino Bartali]]\n| mountains_nat      = ITA\n| mountains_natvar   = 1861\n| mountains_team     = Italy\n| previous           = [[1937 Tour de France|1937]]\n| next               = [[1939 Tour de France|1939]]\n}}\nThe '''1938 Tour de France''' was the 32nd edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place from 5 to 31 July. It was composed of 21 stages over {{convert|4694|km|0|abbr=on}}.The race was won by Italian cyclist [[Gino Bartali]], who also won the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]].\n\n==Changes from the previous Tour==\nThe bonification system was reduced compared to 1937: the winner of a stage now only received one minute bonification time, added by the margin to the second arriving cyclist, with a maximum of 75 seconds. The cyclists who reached a mountain top that counted towards the mountains classification first, now received only one minute bonification time.<ref name=\"mdc1938\"/>\n\nThe team trial stages, where the teams departed 15 minutes separately, were removed from the race. They would later return in the [[1954 Tour de France]], in a different form.<ref name=\"mdc1938\"/> Instead, the 1938 Tour de France featured two [[individual time trial]]s.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=139\u2013144}}\n\nIn previous years, some cyclists were in teams and other rode individually. In 1937, there had been problems with individual cyclists being accused of helping other cyclists, culminating in the Belgian cyclists leaving the Tour. To avoid these problems, the categories for individual cyclists were removed for the 1938 Tour de France,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.historischekranten.be/issue/DHA/1938-01-02/edition/null/page/9?query=%22ronde%20van%20frankrijk%22&period=1903-1939&sort=issuedate%20ascending|title=De Ronde van Frankrijk|language=Dutch|date=2 January 1938|accessdate=21 May 2014|work=De Halle}}</ref> and the race was contested by national teams. But because there were many French cyclists that did not fit into the national team, there were two extra French teams, the Bleuets and Cadets.<ref name=\"mdc1938\"/> The Bleuets was a kind of French \"B\"-team, while the Cadets consisted of young French promises.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1938.php|title=1938: A final fling for les Bleus|author=Tom James|publisher=VeloArchive|date=15 August 2003|accessdate=20 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1938 Tour de France}}\n\nThe big cycling nations in 1938, Belgium, Italy, Germany and France, each sent a team of 12 cyclists. Other countries, Spain, Luxembourg, Switzerland and the Netherlands, sent smaller teams of six cyclists each. The French had two extra teams of 12 cyclists, the Cadets and Bleuets.<ref name=\"mdc1938\"/>\n\nThe three most powerful teams were the Belgian, the French and the Italian national team.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=139\u2013144}} The Italian team was led by Bartali, who had been close to winning the Tour de France in 1937 until he crashed. The Italian cycling federation had requested him to skip the [[1938 Giro d'Italia]] so he could focus on the Tour de France.<ref name=\"revealed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1938.htm|title=Gino \"the Pious\" Climbs to Victory|year=2004|accessdate=22 January 2010|publisher=Cycling revealed}}</ref>\n\nThe teams entering the race were:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Belgium\n* Italy\n* Germany\n* France\n* Spain\n* Switzerland\n* Netherlands\n* Luxembourg\n* France Cadets\n* France Bleuets\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Route and stages==\n\nThe [[List of highest points reached in the Tour de France|highest point of elevation in the race]] was {{convert|2770|m|ft|abbr=on}} at the summit of the [[Col de l'Iseran]] mountain pass on stage 15.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=178}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Vandaag begint de \"Tour de France\"|trans-title=Today the \"Tour de France\" starts|url=https://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ddd:010474164:mpeg21:p004|work=Het Volksdagblad|date=5 July 1938|page=4|language=Dutch|via=[[Delpher]]}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1938\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1938.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306131829/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1938.php|archive-date=6 March 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=32\u00e8me Tour de France 1938|language=French}}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=36}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1938 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |author=Arian Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWiBhPaH?url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=20 April 2009  }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\