 || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Kint]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 19|19]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |28 July|| [[Metz]] to [[Reims]] ||{{convert|196|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Fabien Galateau]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 28 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Reims]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 20a|20a]]\n|rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |30 July|| [[Reims]] to [[Laon]] ||{{convert|48|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Glauco Servadei]]|ITA|1861}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 20b|20b]]\n| [[Laon]] to [[Saint-Quentin, Aisne|Saint-Quentin]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|42|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Time Trial.svg|link=Individual time trial|20px|alt=]] || [[Individual time trial]] || {{flagathlete|[[F\u00e9licien Vervaecke]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 20c|20c]]\n| [[Saint-Quentin, Aisne|Saint-Quentin]] to [[Lille]] ||{{convert|107|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Neuville]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 21|21]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |31 July|| [[Lille]] to [[Paris]] ||{{convert|279|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}<br/>{{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]|FRA}}<ref group=\"n\">Magne and Leducq were both declared winners of stage 21.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4694|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n==Race overview==\n{{main|1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c|1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21}}\n[[File:Peloton passeert kudde schapen - Cyclists passing a herd of sheep.jpg|Cyclists passing a herd of sheep|thumb|right|alt=A flock of sheep, with behind them around 30 cyclists riding from left to right.]]\nBefore the Pyrenees, all the favourites remained calm. [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]] did not lose much time in the first stages, and when he got in a breakaway in the second part of the sixth stage, he took over the lead from [[Jean Majerus]].{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=139\u2013144}} In the eighth stage, [[Gino Bartali]] attacked, and dropped everybody. On the descent of the Col d'Aspin, his wheel collapsed, and [[F\u00e9licien Vervaecke]] and [[Ward Vissers]] overtook him. Bartali came back to finish in third place, but Vervaecke took the lead in the general classification.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> In that stage, former winner [[Georges Speicher]] was caught holding on to a car, and was removed from the race.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=139\u2013144}}\n\nAfter that stage, Bartali was in second place in the general classification. He won some time on Vervaecke because of bonifications for reaching the tops of the Portet d'Aspet and the Braus first and winning the 11th stage, but lost some time in the individual time trial in stage 10b.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=139\u2013144}}\n\nIn the fourteenth stage, Bartali attacked again, and gained 17 minutes on Vervaecke and 20 on Vissers. Bartali was now leader of the race.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\nBefore the next stage, Bartali felt poorly. His team director, [[Costante Girardengo]], told him not to force himself. Bartali let the others get away on the first mountains, but during the descent of the Iseran, Bartali went as fast as he could, and reach his concurrents. During that stage, [[Mathias Clemens]], who started the stage in second place, lost a lot of time, so Vervaecke was back in second place, 20 minutes behind Bartali.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=139\u2013144}}\n\nIn the rest of the race, Bartali defended his lead with ease. Vervaecke won back some time in the last individual time trial, but that was not enough to endanger Bartali's lead.\n\nIn the last stage, [[Antonin Magne]] (winner of the Tour de France in 1931 and 1934) and [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]] (winner of the Tour de France in 1930 and 1932) escaped together, and crossed the finish line together. The Tour jury declared them both winner.<ref name=\"mdc1938\"/> This was Leducq's 25th and final stage victory.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> For both cyclists it was also the last stage they ever rode in the Tour de France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/2359.html|title=The Tour - Andr\u00e9 Leducq|publisher=Amaury Sport Organisation|accessdate=20 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709033354/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/2359.html|archive-date=9 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/2363.html|title=The Tour - Antonin Magne|publisher=Amaury Sport Organisation|accessdate=20 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726170806/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/2363.html|archive-date=26 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Classification leadership and minor prizes==\n\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish each stage was recorded, and these times were added together for the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]]. If a cyclist had received a time bonus, it was subtracted from this total; all time penalties were added to this total. The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey.\n\nFor the [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]], 12 mountains were selected by the Tour organisation. The Iseran was included for the first time in 1938.<ref name=\"mdc1938\"/> On the top of these mountains, ten points were given for the first cyclist to pass, nine points to the second cyclist, and so on, until the tenth cyclist who got one point. The mountains classification in 1938 was won by [[Gino Bartali]]. Bartali was the first cyclist to win the general classification and the mountains classification of the Tour de France in the same year.{{sfn|Moliterno|2000|p=73}}\n\nThe [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]] was calculated in 1938 by adding up the times of the best three cyclists of a team; the team with the least time was the winner. In 1938, there were eight teams of twelve cyclists. Belgium, Italy, Germany and France had a team, Luxembourg and Switzerland both supplied six cyclists for a combined team, as did Spain and the Netherlands, and there were two extra French teams, the ''bleuets'' and the ''cadets''.<ref name=\"mdc1938\"/> The bleuets were also described as \"France B\", and the cadets as \"France C\".\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:smaller; clear:both;\"\n|+Classification leadership by stage<ref name=\"tdf-statistics\">{{cite web|last=van den Akker|first=Pieter|title=Informatie over de Tour de France van 1938|trans-title=Information about the Tour de France from 1938|url=http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1938|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302050019/http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1938|archivedate=2 March 2019|language=Dutch|website=TourDeFranceStatistieken.nl|accessdate=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1%;\"| Stage\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| Winner\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|25px|link=]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|Mountains classification]]{{refn|No jersey was awarded to the leader of the mountains classification until a white jersey with red [[polka dot]]s was introduced in [[1975 Tour de France|1975]].{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}}|group=\"n\"|name=\"mountains-jersey\"}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:24%;\"| [[Team classification in the Tour de France|Team classification]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 1|1]]\n| [[Willi Oberbeck]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Willi Oberbeck]]\n| rowspan=\"10\"| ''no award''\n| Germany\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 2|2]]\n| [[Jean Majerus]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"7\"| [[Jean Majerus]]\n| rowspan=\"9\"| France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 3|3]]\n| [[Gerrit Schulte]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 4a|4a]]\n| [[\u00c9loi Meulenberg]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 4b|4b]]\n| [[\u00c9loi Meulenberg]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 4c|4c]]\n| [[F\u00e9licien Vervaecke]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 5|5]]\n| [[\u00c9loi Meulenberg]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 6a|6a]]\n| [[Jules Rossi]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 6b|6b]]\n| [[Glauco Servadei]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 7|7]]\n| [[Theo Middelkamp]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 8|8]]\n| [[F\u00e9licien Vervaecke]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"8\"| [[F\u00e9licien Vervaecke]]\n| rowspan=\"19\"| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| rowspan=\"19\"| Belgium\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 9|9]]\n| [[Jean Fr\u00e9chaut]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 10a|10a]]\n| [[Antoon van Schendel]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 10b|10b]]\n| [[F\u00e9licien Vervaecke]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 10c#Stage 10c|10c]]\n| [[Antonin Magne]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 11|11]]\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 12|12]]\n| [[Jean Fr\u00e9chaut]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 13|13]]\n| [[Dante Gianello]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 14|14]]\n| [[Gino Bartali]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"11\"| [[Gino Bartali]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 15|15]]\n| [[Marcel Kint]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 16|16]]\n| [[Marcel Kint]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 17a|17a]]\n| [[\u00c9mile Masson Jr.]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 17b|17b]]\n| [[Jean Fr\u00e9chaut]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 18|18]]\n| [[Marcel Kint]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 19|19]]\n| [[Fabien Galateau]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 20a|20a]]\n| [[Glauco Servadei]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 20b|20b]]\n| [[F\u00e9licien Vervaecke]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 20c|20c]]\n| [[Fran\u00e7ois Neuville]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1938 Tour de France, Stage 11 to Stage 21#Stage 21|21]]\n| [[Antonin Magne]]<br />[[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Final\n! style=\"background:#FFDB00;\"|[[Gino Bartali]]\n! [[Gino Bartali]]\n! Belgium\n|}\n\n==Final standings==\n\n===General class